cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 45 mi NNW of Key West, or 65 mi S of Naples, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: Moving west-northwest away from the Keys into the southeast Gulf of Mexico, then expected to slow, stall, and turn northward mid-week toward Florida’s central/northern Gulf Coast
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Gulf Coast (likely Big Bend region)

weather_observation.watch_coast: None in effect for Florida west coast after 09 Nov 04 UTC advisory
weather_observation.warning_coast: Florida coast from Brevard/Volusia County line around Cape Canaveral westward and southward to Anna Maria Island, including Tampa Bay and the Keys
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Entire south and central Florida peninsula, Florida Keys, and Florida Gulf Coast from Naples northward through Tampa Bay and Big Bend
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force winds (35–45 kt) with occasional gusts near 50 kt possible Wednesday–Thursday as Eta passes west of Tampa Bay.
weather_observation.storm_surge: Minor surge of 1–2 ft possible in Tampa Bay and along the immediate Manatee County shoreline if onshore flow develops.
weather_observation.rainfall: 2–4 in. with locally higher amounts up to 6 in. possible through Thursday; could produce pooling on terminals and short-term flooding of access roads.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Isolated tornadoes in outer rainbands; dangerous rip currents and rough seas affecting vessel approaches.
